[thinking] **Exploring package-private annotations**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I’m thinking about package-private top-level annotations in the same file and how they relate to libraries and tests. If a source is compiled in the same package, it can use package-private annotations, but I want to keep tests outside library packages. Still, if the ECJ compiles it, can it handle annotations with the same fully qualified name? It seems like there are ways for it to work out, as long as the classpath doesn’t lead to duplicates.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Considering JavaCompiler requirements**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm contemplating that the JavaCompiler might only need the java.base module, as the processor is already loaded and can use its own class. It doesn’t necessarily require the compiled annotation on the processor's classpath. I can define package-private top-level annotations, interfaces, and enums in the same test file while compiling source strings for the same fully qualified names. Even with duplicate type names, it seems manageable, especially since standard Java allows one public class alongside package-private top-level types. So, that sounds good!
[thinking] 
