[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring package-private annotations**\n\nI’m thinking about package-private top-level annotations in the same file and how they relate to libraries and tests. If a source is compiled in the same package, it can use package-private annotations, but I want to keep tests outside library packages. Still, if the ECJ compiles it, can it handle annotations with the same fully qualified name? It seems like there are ways for it to work out, as long as the classpath doesn’t lead to duplicates.\n\n**Considering JavaCompiler requirements**\n\nI'm contemplating that the JavaCompiler might only need the java.base module, as the processor is already loaded and can use its own class. It doesn’t necessarily require the compiled annotation on the processor's classpath. I can define package-private top-level annotations, interfaces, and enums in the same test file while compiling source strings for the same fully qualified names. Even with duplicate type names, it seems manageable, especially since standard Java allows one public class alongside package-private top-level types. So, that sounds good!\n\n**Considering Java compilation options**\n\nI'm thinking about using BatchCompiler for annotation processing. I need to check if the ECJ version supports Java 17. Version 3.26.0 from Eclipse 2021 likely supports Java 16. I wonder if my test source needs to avoid modern features since it’s compiled by JDK 21. Using the correct source and target version is essential—maybe I should consider passing -source 11 and -target 11 to keep it simple. I also need to ensure my class names follow naming rules.\n\n**Exploring class naming rules**\n\nI’m considering how the naming rules apply to test class or file names versus inner classes. It looks like generating top-level helper classes could help. I might go with package-private top-level classes to minimize inner name usage, while keepi