 17. Version 3.26.0 from Eclipse 2021 likely supports Java 16. I wonder if my test source needs to avoid modern features since it’s compiled by JDK 21. Using the correct source and target version is essential—maybe I should consider passing -source 11 and -target 11 to keep it simple. I also need to ensure my class names follow naming rules.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class naming rules**\\n\\nI’m considering how the naming rules apply to test class or file names versus inner classes. It looks like generating top-level helper classes could help. I might go with package-private top-level classes to minimize inner name usage, while keeping one public top-level test class. I wonder if I can have a package-private processor in the same file. It seems important to maintain a one-to-one mapping between the dynamic-access report classes and the generated test class files.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_wPY7ZyscbSHS92tJYTaAKqvk|fc_0792030059ec0cf80169f0e71914548195933e6970130668f5", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.eclipse.jdt/ecj/3.26.0/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2746, "output": 3163, "cacheRead": 24576, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30485, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777395432550, "responseId": "resp_0792030059ec0cf80169f0e6e901108195837cb21bbedf4db3"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_wPY7ZyscbSHS92tJYTaAKqvk|fc_0792030059ec0cf80169f0e71914548195933e6970130668f5", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"rules\": [\n    {\n      \"excludeClasses\": \"**\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"includeClasses\": \"org.eclipse.jdt.**\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777395481586}]}
